## 3. Challenge 1 — The target is wrong for who you are

Wave 2 trains on `y = int(close[d+h] > close[d])`: binary, daily, up-or-down. You are a directional options **buyer**. Those two facts are in direct conflict, and the conflict is fatal in three compounding ways.

**(a) It is the least achievable target in the discipline.** The plan itself cites the ceiling: ~53–57% honest out-of-sample, with anything higher being leakage. So this aims your scarcest resources — clean data and validation budget — at the one prediction where the realistic ceiling is lowest and the overfitting temptation is highest.

**(b) It is nearly useless to a buyer even when it is right — and this is the part that rarely gets said.** A buyer loses money being *right on direction* constantly. Here is the math that proves it:

When you buy an at-the-money option, your breakeven is roughly the strike plus the premium, and the premium is approximately the *straddle-implied move*. To profit, the realized move must **exceed the implied move**, in your direction, **before theta decays it**. But "the option is priced fairly" means *exactly* that implied move equals expected realized move. So buying premium is a bet that realized will beat implied — and structurally, on average, it does not: the **volatility risk premium is typically positive (implied > realized)**, which is precisely why selling premium is the crowded retail trade and buying it bleeds.

A directional model that is 55% right on *sign* tells you nothing about whether the move will clear the implied move. On average it will not. Then subtract the bid-ask spread and STT, and a 55% sign signal is *dominated by costs* before it ever reaches your P&L. Direction sign is a seller's luxury and a buyer's trap.

What a buyer actually needs is the **joint** picture — direction **and** magnitude **and** timing **and** the vol path — because the option only pays if the move clears the premium before decay eats it. Wave 2 predicts the single dimension that, alone, cannot tell you whether to buy.

**(c) It is the most overfit-seductive target.** A high accuracy number on daily direction is the precise red flag your entire product exists to be the opposite of. Optimizing toward it courts the exact failure mode (multiple-testing, rule-recovery, leakage) that produces the "91% of F&O traders lose money" outcome.

Three strikes on one target: least achievable, least useful, most dangerous.

**→ The alteration.** Replace "predict daily index direction" as the wave's headline objective. Direction, if predicted at all, becomes a *last-priority, regime-conditioned, abstaining* signal — never the engine. The new primary targets are defined in Section 9.

