## 4. Challenge 2 — The 50-row reality makes the entire headline stack inactive

This is the most important technical objection, because it is quantitative and the plan cannot argue with it.

On ~50 rows per underlying, **every headline capability the plan promises is inactive by the plan's own rules.** Walk the stack:

**The model overfits structurally.** ~50 rows against ~15–20 features is roughly **3 rows per feature**. Gradient-boosted trees need hundreds to thousands of rows to avoid memorizing noise; even an L2 logistic is shaky at 3:1. Whatever fits will be overfit, and you will not be able to tell, because —

**The gate's own verdict is unreliable at this n.** CPCV partitions the data into groups and tests combinations; with embargo ≥ horizon (5 days), each fold *loses* 5–10 rows. You are computing DSR and PBO on train/test splits of a dozen rows each. Those statistics are themselves high-variance at this sample size — the gate cannot reliably distinguish real edge from noise, which means even a *passing* verdict would not be trustworthy.

**Calibration — the product's defining feature — degrades to the identity function.** `fit_best_calibrator` falls back to identity when n < ~30. With ~50 total rows and an OOS hold-out for calibration, the calibration set is ~10 points. Isotonic regression on 10 points is a 3-step staircase; Platt on 10 points is barely identifiable. So by the plan's own rule, on current data the "**calibrated probability**" — the one number you have promised to show — is just the **raw, uncalibrated model output**. The headline feature is switched off.

**Conformal bands are noise.** Split-conformal computes the (1−α) nonconformity quantile from the calibration set. With ~10 points, that quantile is essentially "the max of ten numbers." The bands carry no real coverage guarantee at this n.

**Meta-labeling is impossible, not merely optional.** It is a *second* model trained on the *first* model's errors. The first model has ~50 rows; its errors number ~20–25 cases. You cannot train a classifier on 20 cases. The plan correctly flags it optional — but that flag understates it: the whole edifice is data-starved three to four layers deep.

Put it together. Until W3's data arrives, Phases A, B, and C ship a system that produces: **an uncalibrated raw probability, with noise bands, and no edge badge** — functionally indistinguishable from the RND baseline you *already have*, but with roughly ten new modules to maintain. You would be writing sophisticated ML infrastructure whose every distinguishing feature is dormant.

This is the crux of "why not build it now." It is not a matter of taste. At 50 rows, the ML engine *cannot be different from the baseline*, by arithmetic.

**→ The alteration.** Do not build the ML stack against current data. The data wave is not a *later* dependency of the ML wave — it is a *prerequisite* of it. Acquire history first (Section 10), then the same modules become live instead of dormant.

