## 5. Challenge 3 — The sequence is backwards; data is the binding constraint

Wave 2 places the ML engine before the data (W2 builds the engine, W3 acquires the multi-year history that "unlocks validated edge"). This is the third plan running to defer data, and it is the root cause of the empty-product problem in Section 2.

The binding constraint on this entire project is not model sophistication. It is sample size. With 62 days you cannot validate anything; with 3–5 years your structural estimates become statistically reliable, your gate's n≥50 becomes n≥1000+, `edge_verified` can actually light up, and the headline feed can populate. Every other component you have already built — the RND, the GEX read, the IV-crush logic, the regime classifier, the calibration ledger — is **dormant for the same reason**: it has too little history to clear the gate. Data is the one input that converts all of it from scaffolding to live at once.

There is a real counter-argument, and it deserves a fair hearing: building the harness now means it is *ready* when data lands, and Phase A is cheap (zero new deps). True. But the opportunity cost is the thing that has burned you three times — engineering hours spent on a dormant engine are hours not spent on the one input that lights up everything you already own. Readiness is not the bottleneck. Data is.

**→ The alteration.** Promote the data acquisition to the *front* of the wave (it becomes the new Wave 2, or runs concurrently and *ahead of* any new ML work). The ML engine follows the data, not the reverse.

