## 11. What to build instead — the reframed targets

This is the constructive core. Replace "predict daily direction" with a small set of targets ranked by *(achievability × usefulness to a buyer)*. Each is more honest, more useful, and — critically — most are **more data-efficient** than a single daily direction label.

**1. Probability of touch + expected-move calibration (highest priority).** "What is P(NIFTY tags strike K within horizon T), and is the option pricing that fairly?" This is the buyer's *actual* question, directly actionable for strike selection, and defensibly calibratable from the Breeden–Litzenberger risk-neutral density you **already compute** (`implied_dist.py`) plus a realized-vs-implied adjustment. Two decisive advantages: it is where a real, honest 65–70% calibrated number lives; and — this is the under-appreciated part — **every strike × every horizon × every day is a separately resolvable forecast**, so touch/no-touch generates *vastly* more labels per unit time than one direction label per horizon. The touch framing is not only more useful, it *partially solves the data problem* by multiplying your calibration sample. Double win.

**2. Volatility risk premium / IV richness.** "Is this option cheap or expensive versus the realized vol that will likely show up?" Compute implied (ATM IV — you have it) versus a realized-vol forecast (GARCH via `arch`, or HAR-RV / EWMA to start). VRP = IV − E[RV]. The signal: the *rare* windows where VRP is low or negative (premium-buying favorable) versus the usual state where it is high (unfavorable). This is among the most documented edges in the literature (your Baltussen citation), it is mostly statistical (ML only refines it), and for a buyer it directly answers the most important question — *when is buying premium +EV at all*.

**3. Event-conditioned IV-crush magnitude.** Build an events calendar (earnings, RBI, budget, weekly/monthly expiry). Measure historical IV behavior per event type — run-up, crush magnitude, post-event realized. Predict the crush; gate buying into it. Predicting crush magnitude is far more tractable than predicting direction, and the *abstention* it produces ("do not buy premium into this crush") is itself alpha.

**4. Regime classification (trend / range / squeeze).** Whether directional buying makes sense *at all* is regime-dependent. An HMM (`hmmlearn`) or even rules over (realized vol, GEX sign, trend strength, IV term-structure) classify the state and calibrate transition probabilities. This is genuinely where GBM/HMM earns its keep, and it *routes* which other signals are trusted.

**5. Direction — last, and only conditioned + abstaining.** If predicted at all: condition on regime, surface *only* on the gated subset where conformal abstention says you are confident, accept ~60–65% on ~15% coverage, and never let it be the headline.

Underneath all five, the deliverable stays **calibration, not accuracy** — Brier score, the live reliability diagram, the risk-coverage curve. That spine is already built. Lean all the way into it. The ML layer (Section 6) then sits *on top* of targets 1–4, consuming them as features and deciding act/abstain.

